d Its Successors -- tThe State and Public Opinion -- tThe Crisis of Modernity -- tNeo- Hasidism -- tSECTION 3 - DEATH AND RESURRECTION: The Twentieth and Twenty- First Centuries -- tIntroduction: The Twentieth and Twenty-First Centuries -- tPART I. BETWEEN WORLD WAR I AND WORLD WAR II -- tWar and Revolution -- tIn a Sovereign Poland -- tHungary, Czechoslovakia, and Romania -- tAmerica and the Land of Israel -- tKhurbn: Hasidism and the Holocaust -- tPART II. POSTWAR PHOENIX: HASIDISM AFTER THE HOLOCAUST -- tAmerica: Hasidism's Goldene Medinah -- tThe State of Israel: Haven in Zion -- tHasidic Society -- tHasidic Culture -- tIn the Eyes of Others: Hasidism in Contemporary Culture -- tAfterword -- tAnnotated Bibliography -- tAbout the Authors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe first comprehensive history of the pietistic movement that shaped modern JudaismThis is the first comprehensive history of the pietistic movement that shaped modern Judaism. The book's unique blend of intellectual, religious, and social history offers perspectives on the movement's leaders as well as its followers, and demonstrates that, far from being a throwback to the Middle Ages, Hasidism is a product of modernity that forged its identity as a radical alternative to the secular world.Hasidism originated in southeastern Poland, in mystical circles centered on the figure of Israel Ba'al Shem Tov, but it was only after his death in 1760 that a movement began to spread. Challenging the notion that Hasidism ceased to be a creative movement after the eighteenth century, this book argues that its first golden age was in the nineteenth century, when it conquered new territory, won a mass following, and became a mainstay of Jewish Orthodoxy. World War I, the Russian Revolution, and the Holocaust decimated eastern European Hasidism. But following World War II, the movement enjoyed a second golden age, growing exponentially. Today, it is witnessing a remarkable renaissance in Israel, the United States, and other countries around the world.Written by an international team of scholars, Hasidism is a must-read for anyone seeking to understand this vibrant and influential modern Jewish movement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 27. Sep 2021) 0aHasidismxHistory. 7aRELIGION / Judaism / History.2bisacsh1 aAssaf, David, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBiale, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Benjamin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aGreen, Arthur, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGreen, Arthur.1 aHeilman, Samuel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aRosman, Moshe, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aSagiv, Gadi, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWodziński, Marcin, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPrinceton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311060659140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781400889198zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781400889198423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781400889198/original  a978-3-11-060659-1  Princeton University Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK